7838,1,'2017-05-29 15:39:21','2017-05-29 15:39:21','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at things until I get the result I\'m after. Once I was successful (yay!) - I put together a neat little list of notes that I will share with you here, to hopefully spare you some unnecessary pain.\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 1</h5>\r\n<strong>SSH into your server.</strong>\r\n<p>This is the first thing. You need to get shell access and be able to log in. The first thing you\'ll see when you log in is this.</p> <img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-47839\" src=\"https://redrambles.blog//wp-content/uploads/2017/05/skymaster.png\" alt=\"skymaster\" width=\"467\" height=\"234\" /> <p>I went around the house saying \'SKYMASTEERRRRRR\' for an hour - bless you if this also brought you joy. Also could have been the wine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once you\'ve gotten over the Skymaster thing, you\'ll find that you are in your home directory. You should see a site folder there called \'name-you-picked.dreamhoster.com\' if you are using the temporary domain that you are given when you sign up. If you linked your own domain to Dreamhost - you will see your domain name there \'your-awesome-domain-name.something\'.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>We are going to create another directory to keep our site directory company, called \'repo\' </strong> - and then we will move into it.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir repo &amp;&amp; cd repo</code>\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 2</h5>\r\nNext, we will <strong>create a new directory called \'sitename.git\' and move into it</strong>. I\'m just going to call mine \'kittens\'.\r\n\r\n<code>mkdir kittens.git &amp;&amp; cd kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 3</h5>\r\nNice! Now we need to make this into a bare repository.\r\n\r\n<code>git init --bare</code>\r\n\r\nAnd then move into the \'hooks\' directory:\r\n<code>cd hooks</code>\r\n\r\n\r\nIn this hooks directory, there will be a file called \'post-receive\'. <strong>This is what we are going to use in order to deploy our files on the server.</strong> Essentially, we will tell Git: \"Hey! When you receive a push over here - I want you to take it and deploy the files in my site folder please - k thx!\" (Git replies something like: \"k cool, whatevs\").\r\n\r\nHere\'s what we need to put in that your post-receive file:\r\n\r\n<code>#!/bin/sh\r\ngit --work-tree=/home/your_username/your_site_folder.whatever --git-dir=/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git checkout -f</code>\r\n\r\nYou can use \'nano\' or \'vi\' to launch a terminal based editor in order to enter this line of code (edit the ‘your_username’ to be your actual username and ‘your_site_folder’ oh good grief you know this right!?) and then save the file.\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 4</h5>\r\nNext - we need to <strong>make that post-receive file executable</strong>. It\'s like giving it superpowers.\r\n\r\n\r\n<code>chmod +x post-receive</code>\r\n\r\n<h5>Step 5</h5>\r\nNow you can bail out of the server! Woot! Until we meet again, Skymaster. Until we meet again. Back in your local project, you\'ll need to <strong>add a remote connection</strong> to your site. It will look something like this:\r\n\r\n<code>git remote add dreamhost ssh://your_username@your_site_name.whatever/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\nI know.\r\n\r\nThen - you\'ll <strong>push up those files</strong>!\r\n\r\n<code>git push dreamhost master</code>\r\n\r\nThen you dance!!!\r\n\r\nThis is only half of the equation, of course - in order to fully migrate your site, you\'ll also need to move over your database - but the point here is, folks - that you can now deploy your file changes using Git instead of stupid SFTP and you will feel like a total badass.\r\n\r\nSKYMASTERRRRRRRRRR!!!','How to deploy with Dreamhost using Git','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. ','publish','open','open','','how-to-deploy-with-dreamhost-using-git','','','2017-08-22 15:33:00','2017-08-22 15:33:00','',0,'https://redrambles.blog//?p=47838',0,'post','',0),(47839,1,'2017-05-29 15:00:26','2017-05-29 15:00:26','dreamhost ssh','skymaster','','inherit','open','closed','','skymaster','','','2017-05-29 15:00:38','2017-05-29 15:00:38','',47838,'https://redrambles.blog//wp-content/uploads/2017/05/skymaster.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(47840,1,'2017-05-29 15:09:14','2017-05-29 15:09:14','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. Right?! Dreamhost say that they support Git, so I figured - righto - let\'s get this show on the road!\r\n\r\nEhhhhhh - This is where things got murky - at least for me. The documentation I unearthed was incomplete at best. Though Git <strong>is</strong> already installed on my Dreamhost server, that was pretty much the end of git support, at least in so far as I found. (sad emoji)\r\n\r\nSo! I decided to do what I always do in these situations: pour myself a glass of wine, put on some good tunes, crack open my terminal and hack at things until I get the result I\'m after. Once I was successful (yay!) - I put together a neat little list of notes that I will share with you here, to hopefully spare you some 