e in order to deploy our files on the server.</strong> Essentially, we will tell Git: \"Hey! When you receive a push over here - I want you to take it and deploy the files in my site folder please - k thx!\" (Git replies something like: \"k cool, whatevs\").\r\n\r\nHere\'s what we need to put in that your post-receive file:\r\n\r\n<code>#!/bin/sh\r\ngit --work-tree=/home/your_username/your_site_folder.whatever --git-dir=/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git checkout -f</code>\r\n\r\nYou can use \'nano\' or \'vi\' to launch a terminal a based editor in order to enter this line of code and then save the file. (edit the ‘your_username’ to be your actual username and ‘your_site_folder’ oh good grief you know this right!?)</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Next - we need to <strong>make that post-receive file executable</strong>. It\'s like giving it superpowers.</li>\r\n\r\n\r\n<code>chmod +x post-receive</code>\r\n\r\n 	<li>Now you can bail out of the server! Woot! Until we meet again, Skymaster. Until we meet again. Back in your local project, you\'ll need to <strong>add a remote connection</strong> to your site. It will look something like this:\r\n\r\n<code>git remote add dreamhost ssh://your_username@your_site_name.wahetever/home/your_username/repo/kittens.git</code>\r\n\r\nI know.\r\n\r\nThen - you\'ll <strong>push up those files</strong>!\r\n\r\n<code>git push dreamhost master</code>\r\n\r\nThen you dance!!!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis is only half of the equation, of course - in order to fully migrate your site, you\'ll also need to move over your database - but the point here is, folks - that you can now deploy your file changes using Git instead of stupid SFTP and you will feel like a total badass.\r\n\r\nSKYMASTERRRRRRRRRR!!!','Dreamhost and Git - how to deploy from local to live.','You have a local project, you\'ve put it under version control and now you want to use Git\'s awesome powers to push all of your files over to your live site - because SFTP blows. ','inherit